# Project Frame Wireless - Advanced Implementation Plan

Thank you for the detailed feedback. This plan outlines how we will completely revamp the application to achieve perfection, implementing powerful file management, seamless mobile navigation, and intuitive desktop interactions.

## Goal Description
Transform Project Frame Wireless from a basic network hub into a full-fledged, high-performance remote file manager and app launcher, seamlessly blending the strengths of Node.js (UI/Drag-and-Drop) and Python (Advanced File Handling/Networking).

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Large File Uploads (12GB Limit)**
> To achieve fast, reliable file transfers up to 12GB without crashing the Python server or eating up RAM, we will **stream** the files directly from the mobile browser to the Python backend chunk-by-chunk. We will use a direct binary upload approach rather than complex multi-part forms to ensure maximum performance.

> [!WARNING]
> **Full PC Access & Security**
> Exposing "This PC" (all drives) is powerful but risky. The Python backend will be updated to:
> 1. Dynamically list all available drives (`C:\`, `D:\`, etc.).
> 2. Strictly filter out system files, hidden files, and protected directories to prevent accidental damage or viewing of sensitive OS data. 
> 3. Enforce **Read-Only** access for browsing, with modifications limited *only* to the dedicated Upload functionality.

## Proposed Changes

### 1. Advanced Python Backend (`backend/server.py`)
- **[MODIFY] Global Access Mode**: Instead of locking into one shared folder, the server will now support navigating from a root "This PC" view showing all drives.
- **[MODIFY] Hidden File Filter**: Use Windows-specific attribute checking (`ctypes`) to accurately hide system and hidden files.
- **[MODIFY] Upload API Endpoint (`/api/upload`)**: Implement a new `POST` endpoint that accepts raw binary streams and saves them to the currently viewed directory on the PC, supporting massive file sizes chunk-by-chunk.
- **[MODIFY] App List Sync**: The server will load the saved Quick Launch apps (stored by Electron) so they can be sent to the mobile device.

### 2. Enhanced Mobile UI (`public/mobile/`)
- **[MODIFY] Navigation (Fix Back Button)**: Implement the HTML5 History API (`history.pushState`). This will make your phone's native back button correctly navigate up a folder instead of exiting the browser!
- **[MODIFY] 3-Button Item Layout**: Redesign the file list. Each item will have:
    1. **View/Open** (Primary click)
    2. **Pull** (Download icon on the right)
    3. **Info/Select** (Properties icon on the right)
- **[MODIFY] Floating Upload Button**: A clean, modern floating action button to select files from your phone and send them to the current PC directory.
- **[MODIFY] Remote Launcher Section**: A new tab/section in the mobile UI displaying your PC's Quick Launch apps, allowing you to trigger them with a tap.

### 3. Intuitive Desktop UI (`index.html` & `src/renderer.js`)
- **[MODIFY] Drag & Drop**: Completely overhaul the Quick Launch panel. You will be able to literally drag `.exe` or `.bat` files from your Windows Desktop straight into the app's grid to add them instantly.
- **[MODIFY] Quick Launch Sync**: Ensure the saved apps are written to a shared configuration file (e.g., `apps.json`) that the Python server can read and serve to the mobile device.

## Verification Plan
1. **Drag and Drop**: Drag a `.bat` file into the Electron window and verify it is added.
2. **Mobile Navigation**: Browse deep into a folder on the phone, press the physical back button, and verify it goes up one directory.
3. **File Transfer**: Use the upload button on the phone to send a large file to the PC.
4. **App Launching**: Tap an app in the mobile UI and verify it launches on the PC.
